            <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
                <h2 class="text-5xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-12 text-center bg-gradient-to-r from-primary-600 to-purple-600 dark:from-primary-400 dark:to-purple-400 bg-clip-text text-transparent">
                    Global Awareness & Ethics
                </h2>
                <div class="glass-card p-8 md:p-12 space-y-6 text-lg text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
                    <p>
                        Building technology, especially for a diverse and global audience, carries significant ethical weight. My work on the Aadhaar Crowd Management System provided a direct case study in these considerations.
                    </p>
                    
                    <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mt-6 mb-3">Case Study: Data Privacy in Civic Tech</h3>
                    <p>
                        The Aadhaar system, by definition, handles Personally Identifiable Information (PII). This presented several ethical dilemmas:
                    </p>
                    <ul class="mt-4 list-disc list-outside ml-5 space-y-2">
                        <li><strong class="font-medium text-primary-600 dark:text-primary-400">Data Security vs. Usability:</strong> We needed to secure user data with JWTs and robust authentication, but the system also had to be accessible to administrators. We implemented role-based access control (RBAC) to ensure administrators could only see the minimum data necessary (e.g., appointment time, not full user details).</li>
                        <li><strong class="font-medium text-primary-600 dark:text-primary-400">Digital Inclusion:</strong> A significant portion of the user base in India may have low digital literacy or limited internet access. This global issue framed our design. While our solution was web-based, we discussed a parallel SMS-based booking system as a future iteration to ensure equitable access for those without smartphones.</li>
                        <li><strong class="font-medium text-primary-600 dark:text-primary-400">Algorithmic Fairness:</strong> The slot-booking algorithm itself had to be fair. We consciously avoided any logic that could be "gamed" or prioritize users from certain locations, opting for a transparent, first-come-first-served model for all available slots.</li>
                    </ul>

                    <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mt-6 mb-3">Personal Reflection</h3>
                    <p>
                        This project solidified my belief that an engineer's responsibility extends beyond writing functional code. We are architects of systems that can either perpetuate or mitigate societal inequalities. This experience has committed me to championing principles like "privacy by design" and "equitable access" in all my future work.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

